messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Analysis result

- Primary programming language: Go (Golang)
  - Evidence: The project uses a Go module (go.mod) and has Go source files (e.g., hello.go). The module path is github.com/gothinkster/golang-gin-realworld-example-app, which clearly indicates a Go project.
  - go.mod shows standard Go module metadata (module name and Go version).

- Primary web framework: Gin (github.com/gin-gonic/gin)
  - Evidence: hello.go imports "github.com/gin-gonic/gin" and uses gin.Default(), router groups (e.g., /api, /articles, /users), and API registrations. This demonstrates Gin as the main HTTP framework.
  - The module name/given file naming (golang-gin-realworld-example-app) also points to Gin being the chosen framework.

- Optional/secondary tech (for context)
  - ORM: GORM v1 (github.com/jinzhu/gorm) used for migrations and DB interactions (see AutoMigrate calls in the Migrate function in hello.go).
  - DB drivers: go.mod shows indirect dependencies for SQL drivers (mysql, pq for PostgreSQL, sqlite3), indicating multi-database support, though the code sample in hello.go uses GORM to migrate models.

What this tells you about the project
- This is the RealWorld backend example implemented in Go using the Gin framework (a Go web framework) with GORM as the ORM. The code structure (articles, users, common) and API group setup under /api align with the typical RealWorld backend pattern.

If you want deeper confirmation, I can inspect more files (e.g., articles/users packages) to show concrete route definitions or model structures, but the evidence above already points to Go + Gin as the primary language and framework.
